04708nam a22005295i 9780773564220DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735642207 a10.1515/97807735642202doi  a(DE-B1597)656829  a(OCoLC)181843237  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX9225.S46bS56 2001eb 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a230 .5233 0922211 aSkoczylas, Anne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMr Simson's Knotty Case :bDivinity, Politics, and Due Process in Early Eighteenth-Century Scotland /cAnne Skoczylas. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v3100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations Used in the Notes -- tIntroduction: Scotland after 1707 -- tJohn Simson: Historiography and Significance -- tSimson, Glasgow, And Calvinism -- tMy Great Unfitness for Discharging such ane Office Aright: John Simson and Glasgow University -- tI Profess myself only a Student: Simson as Teacher -- tSo Unspotted a Church: Challenges to Scottish Calvinism -- tsimson’s first case -- tA General Inclination to Novelties in Doctrine: Letters, Negotiations, Skirmishes, 1711–1715 -- tA Speedy Trial: Libel, Committee, Trial, 1715–1717 -- tsimson and the struggles in scotland, 1717–1726 -- tAdiew to the Piece and Unity of this place: Simson and Glasgow Politics -- tFurther Gulps of Error: Simson and Religious Turmoil -- tsimson’s second case and after -- tA Crime Deeper than Crimson: From Letter to Suspension, 1726–1727 -- tThe Brink of a Rupture: Depose? Acquit? 1727–1729 -- tQuit of him at last: Descent into Obscurity, 1729–1740 -- tConclusion: Scotland Transformed -- tDocuments re Simson’s First Case -- tDocuments re Simson’s Second Case -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe issues involved in these trials included the right of universities to discipline their professors, the degree of political control over the appointment and methodology of teachers, the preservation of factional advantage through such appointments, and the nature of the relationship between a state church and the public institutions responsible for educating its clergy. Skoczylas shows that the effect of the Enlightenment on Scottish Calvinism, which required adaptation to new developments in theology and pedagogy, was an important sub-text to the trials: the compromise reached at the end of the second led indirectly to the first secession of ultra-orthodox ministers from the Church of Scotland. More significantly, the Church became increasingly open to innovative thought so that enlightened ministers of the latter half of the century could debate matters forbidden to Simson. Mr Simson's Knotty Case breaks new ground, offering the first analysis of many ecclesiastical and political sources. Skoczylas shows that although Simson was in many ways a conservative man, despite his innovative pedagogy, the liberalizing effects of his cases thrust Scotland from the obscurity of Covenanting orthodoxy into the clarity of the Enlightenment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectronic books. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356422040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564220423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9